java.util.Map<K,V>
public class LUCICabinetMap_Shard<K extends java.io.Serializable,V extends java.io.Serializable>
extends LUCICabinetMap<K,V>

This class implements a sharded database. This means that key-value pairs are stored in a collection of different databases based on a function of their key. A sharded database speeds up concurrent access and enables scaling to large databases (in theory).

Constructor Detail

LUCICabinetMap_Shard

public LUCICabinetMap_Shard(java.util.List<LUCICabinetMap<K,V>> shards,
                            boolean optimize)
Parameters:
shards - A list of databases to shard across. If any of these databases are the same database, or are remote wrappers for the same database, then iterations will go across each copy of the database one time (effectively iterating more than once across entries) which is probably not what you want. The sharding function is the default based on a modulo of the hash function.
optimize - If the database is "optimized" then put and removes will be non-blocking and will always return null. This is a violation of the java Map contract, but cuts the database operations in half.

LUCICabinetMap_Shard

public LUCICabinetMap_Shard(java.util.List<LUCICabinetMap<K,V>> shard,
                            ShardFunction sf,
                            boolean optimize)
Parameters:
shard - A list of databases to shard across. If any of these databases are the same database, or are remote wrappers for the same database, then iterations will go across each copy of the database one time (effectively iterating more than once across entries) which is probably not what you want.
sf - An object which defines how to associate keys with shards.
optimize - If the database is "optimized" then put and removes will be non-blocking and will always return null. This is a violation of the java Map contract, but cuts the database operations in half.
